To achieve the layout change for different screen sizes (desktop vs mobile), you can employ CSS media queries along with Flexbox order or CSS Grid techniques to reorder the components only for mobile viewports without changing your React component structure. Since your component structure involves `<Nav />` and the `<NavLink>` with your logo, let’s focus on how to swap these elements in mobile view while keeping your desktop layout as is.

First, ensure your `MainHeader` and `#title` divs are using Flexbox or CSS Grid with appropriate configurations that allow child element reordering. I'll show examples using both Flexbox (`order`) and CSS Grid (`grid-template-areas, grid-area`).

### Using Flexbox

You can assign CSS classes to both the `<Nav />` and the logo `<NavLink>` elements and use the `order` property to rearrange them on mobile screens.

1. **Add classNames to your elements for targeting:**
```jsx
<div id='title' className="header-content">
  <NavLink to="/" className="navbar-brand">
    <img src="images/lemill_shop_logo.png" width="100" alt="my logo img" className="logo" />
  </NavLink>
  <Nav className="navbar-nav" />
  {/* ...rest of your content */}
</div>
```

2. **Apply CSS using the styled-components or an external stylesheet:**
```css
.header-content {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
}

/* Default order for mobile */
.navbar-brand { 
  order: 2; 
}

.navbar-nav { 
  order: 1; 
}

/* Desktop view */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .header-content {
    flex-direction: row; /* Adjust if needed to match your layout */
  }
  .navbar-brand,
  .navbar-nav {
    order: 0; /* Resets to the natural order */
  }
}
```

### Using CSS Grid

If you're using CSS Grid, you can define areas and rearrange them based on the viewport size.

1. **Enhanced HTML structure remains the same as above**.

2. **Apply CSS using styled-components or an external stylesheet:**
```css
.header-content {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-areas: "nav logo"; /* Logo after nav for mobile */
  grid-template-columns: auto; /* Adjust based on your design */
}

/* Desktop view */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .header-content {
    grid-template-areas: "logo nav"; /* Logo before nav (or your preferred layout) */
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, auto); /* Adjust based on your design */
  }
}

.navbar-brand { grid-area: logo; }
.navbar-nav { grid-area: nav; }
```

In both examples, we rearrange elements visually without altering the DOM order itself, thus maintaining SEO best practices and accessibility. Remember to adjust breakpoints (`768px` in this case) and CSS according to your specific design requirements.

To dynamically change the size of your cart trolley icon (`<FiShoppingCart />`) based on screen size, specifically making its size `15` on mobile devices, you can utilize CSS for a responsive design approach instead of directly altering the `size` prop of the `<FiShoppingCart />` component based on the viewport. This is because the `size` prop doesn't support CSS media queries directly. However, you can adjust the icon size using CSS with a combination of `font-size` and media queries.

### Method 1: Encapsulating Icon in a Wrapper

First, wrap your `<FiShoppingCart />` icon in a `div` or `span` to have better control over its size using CSS.

```jsx
<div className="cart-icon-wrapper">
  <NavLink to="/cart" className="navbar-link cart-trolley--link">
    <FiShoppingCart className="cart-trolley" />
    <span className="cart-total--item text-lg"> {total_item} </span>
  </NavLink>
</div>
```

Next, define CSS rules with media queries to adjust the font size of the `.cart-icon-wrapper`. The icon will inherit the `font-size` as its `size`.

```css
.cart-icon-wrapper {
  font-size: 30px; /* Default size for desktop */
}

/* For mobile devices */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .cart-icon-wrapper {
    font-size: 15px; /* Smaller size for mobile */
  }
}
```

### Method 2: Directly Targeting the Icon Class

If you prefer not to wrap the icon or your project structure doesn't allow for it, you can target the `.cart-trolley` class directly. Note that this approach might require adjusting depending on the specific properties of the icons you're using.

```css
/* Default size for desktop */
.cart-trolley {
  width: 30px;
  height: 30px;
}

/* For mobile devices */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .cart-trolley {
    width: 15px;    /* Smaller width for mobile */
    height: 15px;   /* Smaller height for mobile */
  }
}
```

### Using Inline Styles with React (Not Recommended for Responsive Design)

Technically, you could use React state and effects along with event listeners for the viewport size to dynamically change the `size` prop of the `<FiShoppingCart />`, but this approach is more complex and less efficient than using CSS for responsive design. It's generally recommended to handle responsiveness with CSS.

### Conclusion

Depending on your exact setup (e.g., using styled-components or traditional CSS files), you might need to adjust your selectors slightly. However, the principle remains the same: use CSS for responsiveness. Media queries allow you to specify styles that adapt to different screen sizes, making them ideal for changing properties like icon sizes on mobile devices vs. desktops.

