The warning you're encountering "navbar is not defined" and similar for `setMenuIcon` is because of a misuse of variable names and a misunderstanding of the useState hook in your component. Let's correct these issues:

1. **`navbar` is not defined**: This seems to be a typo or a misunderstanding. In your context, `navbar` seems to be intended as a class name string. It should be written in quotes as `"navbar"` for a proper class name definition. 
2. **`setMenuIcon(false)`**: This line is a relic from your initial useState hook that was renamed, but not updated everywhere. As per your current code structure, the correct hook and function to use is `setIsOpen` to manage the open/close state of your navigation bar.

Here is the corrected component considering these points:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from "react";
import { NavLink } from "react-router-dom";
import styled from "styled-components";
import { CgMenu, CgClose } from "react-icons/cg";

const StyledNav = styled.nav`
  .navbar-lists {
    position: relative;
    display: flex;
    gap: 4.8rem;
    align-items: center;

    .navbar-link {
      &:link,
      &:visited {
        display: inline-block;
        text-decoration: none;
        font-size: 17px;
        font-weight: 700;
        letter-spacing: 2px;
        text-transform: capitalize;
        color: white;
        transition: color 0.3s linear;
      }

      &:hover,
      &:active {
        color: #fcb045;
      }
    }
  }

  .mobile-navbar-btn {
    display: none;
    background-color: transparent;
    cursor: pointer;
    border: none;
  }

  @media (max-width: ${({ theme }) => theme.media.mobile}) {
    .mobile-navbar-btn {
      display: inline-block;
      z-index: 9999;
      border: white;

      .mobile-nav-icon {
        font-size: 22px;
        color: white;
      }
    }

    .active .mobile-nav-icon[name="close-outline"] {
      display: none;
    }

    .active .close-outline {
      display: inline-block;
    }

    .navbar-lists {
      width: 100vw;
      height: 100vh;
      position: absolute;
      top: 0;
      left: 0;
      background-color: #fff;
      display: flex;
      justify-content: center;
      align-items: center;
      flex-direction: column;
      visibility: hidden;
      opacity: 0;
      transform: translateX(100%);
      transition: all 0.3s linear;
    }

    .active .navbar-lists {
      visibility: visible;
      opacity: 1;
      transform: translateX(0);
      z-index: 999;
      transition: all 0.3s linear;

      .navbar-link {
        font-size: 4.2rem;
      }
    }
  }
`;

const Nav = () => {
  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);

  return (
    <StyledNav>
      <div className={`${isOpen ? "active" : ""} navbar`}>
        <ul className="navbar-lists">
          {/* Navigation Links */}
          <li><NavLink to="/" className="navbar-link" onClick={() => setIsOpen(false)}>Home</NavLink></li>
          <li><NavLink to="/products" className="navbar-link" onClick={() => setIsOpen(false)}>Products</NavLink></li>
          {/* Add other navigation links similarly */}
        </ul>

        {/* Toggle button for open and close of menu */}
        <button className="mobile-navbar-btn" onClick={() => setIsOpen(!isOpen)}>
          {isOpen ? <CgClose className="mobile-nav-icon" /> : <CgMenu className="mobile-nav-icon" />}
        </button>
      </div>
    </StyledNav>
  );
};

export default Nav;
```

**Key Changes Made:**
- Corrected the class setting for the navbar div to correctly apply the "navbar" class and conditionally toggle the "active" class based on the `isOpen` state.
- Replaced all instances of `setMenuIcon(false)` with `setIsOpen(false)` to correctly reflect the state management function intended for toggling the navigation menu's visibility.

These changes should resolve the warning issues you were experiencing and ensure that your navigation bar's open and close functionality works as expected on mobile devices.

